25
00:03:28,747 --> 00:03:32,330
Rick brings a wealth of knowledge and dedication to the community.

26
00:03:32,850 --> 00:03:39,733
He is a lifelong resident of Medford, having raised his children in the community with his wife of 47 years?

27
00:03:40,874 --> 00:03:43,135
Carol Caraviello is sitting here up front.

28
00:03:44,055 --> 00:03:56,941
He has been an active member of the community, supporting organizations such as the Medford Kiwanis, the Medford Chamber of Commerce, and Medford Youth Hockey, WMCC, where he is no stranger.

29
00:03:57,641 --> 00:04:04,023
He drops by pretty regularly, and he has demonstrated a sincere appreciation for this neighborhood.

30
00:04:04,543 --> 00:04:11,825
Throughout his career, Caraviello has demonstrated a deep commitment to supporting working people and their families.

31
00:04:12,345 --> 00:04:17,606
Rick, welcome to West Memphis Community Center, back, and to First Friday's Words of Music.

32
00:04:17,706 --> 00:04:20,367
First of all, thank you, and it's my honor and privilege to be here this evening.

33
00:04:21,487 --> 00:04:22,488
Excellent, excellent.

34
00:04:22,548 --> 00:04:30,976
So to begin your first Friday's visit to our neighborhood home, I want to get us in to a historical frame of mind.

35
00:04:31,616 --> 00:04:38,843
I write a lot of poetry that speaks to the legacy, mission, and vision of this community.

36
00:04:39,844 --> 00:04:41,485
I want to share a piece of verse.

37
00:04:42,406 --> 00:04:46,269
This is the one that has gotten me almost famous.

38
00:04:47,757 --> 00:05:01,536
It's called Hired by the Mystic, and if you're ever on Mystic Ave, and you go by the Mystic mural, which is on the abutment wall across from the Somerville projects,

39
00:05:03,799 --> 00:05:11,349
25 plus years in the making, two panels painted every year by a muralist by the name of David Fichter, and it's amazing.

40
00:05:11,550 --> 00:05:12,711
It's absolutely amazing.

41
00:05:13,072 --> 00:05:17,758
And the last two panels, which were painted last year and put in place this year,

42
00:05:19,900 --> 00:05:22,501
I had the honor of being on one of the panels.

43
00:05:23,101 --> 00:05:28,283
And then the other panel is a panel of children involved in environmental work.

44
00:05:28,864 --> 00:05:35,167
So if you ever have a chance to see it, you know, go check it out because I think it's an amazing, and not just because I'm on it.

45
00:05:35,647 --> 00:05:40,469
But anyways, a piece of this poem is on that mural as well, and it's called Hired by the Mystic.

46
00:05:41,909 --> 00:05:47,735
They gave my people the lowlands, and not much of it, just a few streets hard by the river.

47
00:05:48,516 --> 00:05:52,179
Banks turned a blind eye behind the red lines, and it wasn't about the money.

48
00:05:53,040 --> 00:05:57,605
Class was an irresistible force, an immovable object.

49
00:05:58,899 --> 00:06:01,181
It wasn't the written rule, but white folks knew the legal.

50
00:06:02,022 --> 00:06:12,531
In our place, in this Mystic Valley space, where slaves and rum and ships had built some mansions, made some millionaires, and hid some old money.

51
00:06:13,372 --> 00:06:14,673
So it was hard by the Mystic.

52
00:06:14,733 --> 00:06:21,799
We went muddy and a bit turned down, the only place where one could be brown in this ancient Middlesex County town.

53
00:06:22,674 --> 00:06:23,595
But we named it.

54
00:06:24,195 --> 00:06:24,956
We claimed it.

55
00:06:25,356 --> 00:06:26,697
We made it our own.

56
00:06:27,658 --> 00:06:34,903
Even in the heat of summer, when the shores were parched and the soil was rank with the decay of aquatic alchemy, we were one with the river.

57
00:06:35,424 --> 00:06:38,306
We followed its flow to the lakes and the sandy beachfront.

58
00:06:39,067 --> 00:06:44,171
On our own Jordan shore, we baptized and blessed our brothers and sisters in Christ.

59
00:06:44,531 --> 00:06:52,137
We caught the little fishes to go with our loaves of bread and became the teeming multitude who our Lord Jesus fed hard by the mystic.

60
00:06:52,777 --> 00:06:53,920
We became community.

61
00:06:54,401 --> 00:06:55,703
We commanded unity.

62
00:06:56,044 --> 00:06:58,609
We raised up our children in the way they should go.

63
00:06:59,858 --> 00:07:03,799
As the river ebbs and flows, the tides will turn and our fortune grows.

64
00:07:04,279 --> 00:07:06,200
A few more streets become our homes.

65
00:07:06,620 --> 00:07:09,281
Houses on Sharon join Kin on Jerome.

66
00:07:09,981 --> 00:07:15,322
From Duggar Park to the railroad tracks, the white folk make more room for blacks.

67
00:07:15,643 --> 00:07:19,644
The color line recedes a bit, church and school and the center sit.

68
00:07:20,344 --> 00:07:23,805
The ville becomes the heart of it, hard by the mystic shores.

69
00:07:24,773 --> 00:07:31,715
Now the worm has surely turned, and folks who left have surely learned things couldn't stay the same.

70
00:07:32,495 --> 00:07:34,655
That muddy mystic most days is clean.

71
00:07:34,675 --> 00:07:36,636
The banks are freshly cut and green.

72
00:07:37,096 --> 00:07:40,496
Faces once distinctly brown are not the only ones in town.

73
00:07:40,556 --> 00:07:46,858
These streets that once were our confines must now embrace what gentry defines.

74
00:07:47,478 --> 00:07:55,302
condominium culture, bedroom convenience, university sprawl, access, egress, invest, and dispossess.

75
00:07:56,343 --> 00:08:04,748
Now those lowlands have become the highlights of a trending city and sometimes that success isn't pretty when it's at the expense of your black and brown and tan friends.

76
00:08:05,879 --> 00:08:11,364
And yet, the river still turns and bends from where it begins to where it ends.

77
00:08:12,025 --> 00:08:22,635
The only place where one could be brown in this ancient Middlesex County town where we named it and claimed it and made it our own.

78
00:08:26,579 --> 00:08:26,999
Thank you.

79
00:08:27,519 --> 00:08:27,860
Thank you.

80
00:08:28,331 --> 00:08:33,332
So that's a little reflection on how this neighborhood came to be.

81
00:08:33,932 --> 00:08:36,133
Let's have a friendly chat with Rick Caraviello.

82
00:08:37,873 --> 00:08:43,214
So Rick, can we talk a bit about what you believe you know about this particular West Memphis neighborhood?

83
00:08:44,355 --> 00:08:47,415
Well, I live right down the street, as many of you know.

84
00:08:48,036 --> 00:08:53,137
And I went to school with everybody in the whole city.

85
00:08:57,205 --> 00:09:06,330
If you look on the wall here, you see many pictures of people who made the center what it is, and I remember many of them growing up, but there's one in particular.

86
00:09:07,490 --> 00:09:09,091
Okay.

87
00:09:09,111 --> 00:09:23,479
13 years ago, when I decided to run for office, as you said, I had always been involved in the community, doing different things, but I was out campaigning, out walking the streets, and I came upon Wally Counts' house.

88
00:09:23,719 --> 00:09:24,740
I didn't know that it was his house,

89
00:09:25,785 --> 00:09:27,506
I rang the bell, it was a hot summer night.

90
00:09:27,767 --> 00:09:29,868
Oh Rick, how you doing?

91
00:09:29,948 --> 00:09:31,369
It's hot, come in and have some water.

92
00:09:31,930 --> 00:09:42,939
So we sat down in his living room with his wife and we had a talk and he said, you know Rick, I've known you a long time, you've always done good for the community.

93
00:09:44,625 --> 00:09:54,669
And he says, I've supported a lot of candidates that I thought were going to be good candidates and do good for the community down here.

94
00:09:55,289 --> 00:09:56,910
He says they didn't live up to their promise.

95
00:10:00,923 --> 00:10:12,714
After an hour of talking and I made a commitment to him that I would always make sure that I'd be down here and take care of this community as long as I was able to.

96
00:10:13,534 --> 00:10:19,880
And I hope Mr. Counts is proud of what he supported 13 years ago.

97
00:10:20,520 --> 00:10:22,902
13 years ago, okay, very good, very good.

98
00:10:26,107 --> 00:10:32,829
Family, I know, you know, because you and I, we talk a lot, is a very important element of your life.

99
00:10:33,349 --> 00:10:37,691
How do you feel that family life has shaped the person that you are today?

100
00:10:38,451 --> 00:10:40,232
Well, you have my wife there.

101
00:10:40,972 --> 00:10:43,053
We've been married 47 years.

102
00:10:43,073 --> 00:10:46,974
And we were both, we got married young.

103
00:10:47,754 --> 00:10:52,356
And I was, you know, young, and my wife,

104
00:10:54,488 --> 00:11:02,113
kind of brought me up, and so I hope that she's proud of the prison that she's developed.

105
00:11:02,133 --> 00:11:08,497
My parents gave her a 22 when she was a little boy, and this is what I've grown up to be, and I owe it all to her.

106
00:11:08,698 --> 00:11:11,199
Oh my gosh, fantastic, fantastic.

107
00:11:11,239 --> 00:11:24,308
Well, you know, you kind of are answering one of the questions that I want to ask you, and maybe you've already answered it in a certain way, but can you talk about who your early role models and heroes were?

108
00:11:26,831 --> 00:11:30,196
I didn't really have any early role models or heroes.

109
00:11:30,837 --> 00:11:32,620
I'm an only child.

110
00:11:33,962 --> 00:11:36,105
My mother passed away a few weeks after I was born.

111
00:11:40,133 --> 00:11:43,075
I don't have like brothers or sisters like other people did.

112
00:11:43,115 --> 00:11:45,136
So being in the NHL is a little different.

113
00:11:45,156 --> 00:11:48,818
So I didn't really have anyone to look up to.

114
00:11:48,838 --> 00:11:50,299
Just my parents, and that was about it.

115
00:11:51,700 --> 00:11:57,943
OK, so we always ask this question when we're with our friends from different places.

116
00:11:58,563 --> 00:11:59,464
Who did you run with?

117
00:11:59,524 --> 00:12:01,625
Who were your pals?

118
00:12:01,665 --> 00:12:02,526
Who were your partners?

119
00:12:04,066 --> 00:12:17,690
Believe it or not, we still hang with our core group of junior high school friends that moved on to high school, and we go out probably every couple of weeks with our core 10 or 12 people.

120
00:12:17,890 --> 00:12:21,631
And Peter Petrella.

121
00:12:22,111 --> 00:12:22,831
I know Petrella.

122
00:12:22,871 --> 00:12:23,771
Peter Petrella.

123
00:12:24,772 --> 00:12:27,012
Pete was in my class, class of 75.

124
00:12:27,052 --> 00:12:27,752
That was the other Peter.

125
00:12:28,553 --> 00:12:29,173
There was two Peters.

126
00:12:29,873 --> 00:12:31,975
It was two Peters, that's Peter the Accountant.

127
00:12:32,015 --> 00:12:32,775
This is his cousin.

128
00:12:33,596 --> 00:12:37,339
Tony Daddario, George Garofalo, Jack Santoro.

129
00:12:40,001 --> 00:12:43,664
We started out the Lincoln Junior High and we remained friends forever.

130
00:12:43,824 --> 00:12:46,085
All right, all right, cool.

131
00:12:46,506 --> 00:12:48,467
That sounds like it would sound if it was coming from me.

132
00:12:48,487 --> 00:12:55,032
And then over the years we took in some of the West Bedford kids, The Clocks, Kenny Mayarco.

133
00:12:55,172 --> 00:12:57,574
Okay, okay, I knew Kenny Mayarco.

134
00:12:59,815 --> 00:13:03,296
And I say, and to this day, we're friends.

135
00:13:03,616 --> 00:13:05,077
And close friends.

136
00:13:06,657 --> 00:13:13,779
So you've been doing the work that you've been doing at City Hall for close to a decade and a half.

137
00:13:14,519 --> 00:13:16,420
What has it taught you about yourself?

138
00:13:19,509 --> 00:13:24,137
I can tell you now, I'm certainly not the same person I was 12 years ago.

139
00:13:24,517 --> 00:13:30,728
I've grown, I've learned, and I've changed my attitude on a lot of things.

140
00:13:31,926 --> 00:13:34,787
It's helped me to grow and grow into a different person.

141
00:13:35,848 --> 00:13:39,829
Though I always had a value system, the value system has changed over the years.

142
00:13:39,849 --> 00:13:46,131
And again, I always managed to stay involved in the community as I am now.

143
00:13:46,512 --> 00:13:47,672
I still belong to the Kiwanis.

144
00:13:47,772 --> 00:13:49,373
I still work at the food bank.

145
00:13:49,693 --> 00:13:50,773
I do work at the library.

146
00:13:50,813 --> 00:13:54,315
So as you know, I've been dedicated to this community my whole life.

147
00:13:54,415 --> 00:13:58,156
And I don't come from, my parents never did this.

148
00:14:00,757 --> 00:14:06,643
Where it came from is when I was like about 45, and I met a friend of mine.

149
00:14:06,683 --> 00:14:10,808
He says, why don't you join a meeting at the corners for us?

150
00:14:10,908 --> 00:14:11,589
I gave his number.

151
00:14:12,430 --> 00:14:18,796
And it was kind of them who shaped me, because we met every week, and it was a bunch of community members.

152
00:14:19,517 --> 00:14:22,659
And I would listen to them, and they would tell the stories of the good things they did.

153
00:14:22,980 --> 00:14:28,064
There was a few political people in there, but they were the ones that actually taught me community service.

154
00:14:28,824 --> 00:14:32,707
And I kind of commend them for doing it.

155
00:14:32,727 --> 00:14:38,852
Yeah, so when we talk about role models and heroes, perhaps some of your role models and heroes came out of that group.

156
00:14:39,072 --> 00:14:44,836
Back then, there was a lot of political people, and there were business and community leaders.

157
00:14:45,877 --> 00:14:50,241
I learned from them, and I aspired to be them.

158
00:14:50,342 --> 00:14:53,385
I was the young kid back then, and they were all older.

159
00:14:53,405 --> 00:14:58,810
But you listen to the stories they would tell, even the politician stories.

160
00:14:59,791 --> 00:15:01,012
They talked about the good things they did.

161
00:15:02,813 --> 00:15:10,318
As I tell even my new counselors, there isn't a better feeling than doing something good for somebody who really needs it.

162
00:15:10,378 --> 00:15:13,800
And I'm not talking about, you know, like Joe Jones calling, hey, can you fix the pothole?

163
00:15:13,820 --> 00:15:18,963
But somebody who really needs help that doesn't relate to your job as a city.

164
00:15:19,664 --> 00:15:23,506
And it's a real good feeling when you do something good for somebody.

165
00:15:25,848 --> 00:15:27,850
I've been to a couple of those Kiwanis meetings.

166
00:15:27,990 --> 00:15:28,810
We're a different group.

167
00:15:29,151 --> 00:15:33,855
Listen, the one thing that you're guaranteed, okay, is the stories.

168
00:15:34,455 --> 00:15:35,056
Absolutely.

169
00:15:35,456 --> 00:15:36,977
The other thing is the food, man.

170
00:15:37,558 --> 00:15:38,439
Y'all like to eat, man.

171
00:15:38,479 --> 00:15:39,279
You don't remember when

172
00:15:44,184 --> 00:15:45,025
Remember the Happy Haddock?

173
00:15:45,045 --> 00:15:45,786
We used to meet there.

174
00:15:46,166 --> 00:15:46,386
Yeah.

175
00:15:46,587 --> 00:15:46,787
Yeah.

176
00:15:46,947 --> 00:15:49,510
And when the Happy Haddock closed, we didn't have a place to go.

177
00:15:50,391 --> 00:15:53,095
And the club almost broke up because over the food.

178
00:15:53,175 --> 00:15:53,976
Yeah.

179
00:15:53,996 --> 00:15:58,381
We were going to eat and finally we ended up going to Bocelli's.

180
00:15:58,401 --> 00:15:59,222
Bocelli's, absolutely.

181
00:15:59,262 --> 00:16:02,306
Yeah, we were going to different places and the food was

182
00:16:03,027 --> 00:16:08,469
was the most important thing and also got the club almost disbanded because we had nowhere to go.

183
00:16:08,569 --> 00:16:09,309
That's too funny.

184
00:16:09,870 --> 00:16:10,330
With food.

185
00:16:10,710 --> 00:16:11,430
Yeah, well.

186
00:16:12,050 --> 00:16:15,072
And I say, you know, I think everybody in the room, you know, it's a family thing.

187
00:16:15,092 --> 00:16:16,412
We all grew up with food.

188
00:16:16,452 --> 00:16:20,474
Food was, you sat around on a Sunday and you had dinner with your family.

189
00:16:20,854 --> 00:16:23,815
I know now that's a forgotten thing, but

190
00:16:24,918 --> 00:16:35,688
I think most of the people in this room, remember you went to your grandparents' house on a Sunday for dinner, or they came to yours, and even as a family, you sat down every night and you had dinner together.

191
00:16:36,068 --> 00:16:39,691
And again, people, everyone does take out, even my own kids I see.

192
00:16:40,916 --> 00:16:42,136
you know, home-cooked meals.

193
00:16:42,416 --> 00:16:46,938
My wife still cooks a meal every night for us and our hosts, and she keeps the tradition going.

194
00:16:47,178 --> 00:16:49,198
Trying to get our kids there is a whole nother thing, though.

195
00:16:49,338 --> 00:16:50,659
I understand, I understand.

196
00:16:51,159 --> 00:16:57,001
But I think it's a tradition, in particular in this community, that's really respected.

197
00:16:57,541 --> 00:17:03,802
And like you say, it doesn't happen nearly as often or as much as it used to, but that's the way we grew up.

198
00:17:04,103 --> 00:17:05,043
It absolutely is.

199
00:17:06,804 --> 00:17:13,467
Okay, so you've been serving the city of Medford for the better part of 12 years, maybe a little bit longer than that.

200
00:17:13,607 --> 00:17:18,530
What has that service taught you about the people that live here in Medford?

201
00:17:19,190 --> 00:17:23,393
It's taught me to respect everybody in this community and to be available to everybody.

202
00:17:23,413 --> 00:17:29,036
I think everybody knows part of the thing is Rick always answers the phone when people call.

203
00:17:29,716 --> 00:17:31,057
I'm always available for everybody.

204
00:17:32,058 --> 00:17:33,458
If you need something, I'll come to your house.

205
00:17:33,498 --> 00:17:34,359
I don't need you to come to me.

206
00:17:36,280 --> 00:17:38,460
And also, I don't like emailing people.

207
00:17:38,500 --> 00:17:39,280
I don't like texting.

208
00:17:39,761 --> 00:17:42,201
If you want something, I'd rather talk to you in person.

209
00:17:43,402 --> 00:17:45,642
Everybody knows if you need something, I'll be at your house.

210
00:17:46,082 --> 00:17:47,183
Anything you ever needed, I'm here.

211
00:17:48,143 --> 00:17:48,683
And that's me.

212
00:17:48,723 --> 00:17:50,604
I'm more of a hands-on type person.

213
00:17:51,284 --> 00:17:52,084
Okay, okay.

214
00:17:52,844 --> 00:18:05,728
So, you know, and again, I mean, these questions kind of bleed into each other in some ways, but, you know, what made you decide, first decide to get involved with city government and run for city council?

215
00:18:08,369 --> 00:18:12,010
Well, as we said earlier, you know, I was always involved with the community and do other things.

216
00:18:14,339 --> 00:18:16,862
I did want to do it at an earlier time.

217
00:18:17,643 --> 00:18:20,906
I remember, I don't know if you remember, remember when they were doing all the gas work over here?

218
00:18:21,487 --> 00:18:23,409
They were tearing up all the streets, putting the gas line in.

219
00:18:23,429 --> 00:18:26,852
There may be some folks who remember it better than I do.

220
00:18:27,673 --> 00:18:33,879
I was kind of, I kind of got involved with that and I was kind of angry because the gas company just wasn't taking care of the people.

221
00:18:34,540 --> 00:18:37,263
And I was, I had thought about running back then, but

222
00:18:39,335 --> 00:18:42,376
You shouldn't run when you're angry or have a cause.

223
00:18:42,756 --> 00:18:49,138
You should run because you want to run to do the right thing and not have a cause.

224
00:18:49,318 --> 00:18:53,640
And my kids had all been grown, so I had the time to dedicate to it.

225
00:18:54,280 --> 00:18:56,401
And I felt it was a good move up for me.

226
00:18:57,461 --> 00:19:04,883
And again, my friends at the Kiwanis, they inspired me to do it because I saw them, I saw many of them there.

227
00:19:06,324 --> 00:19:08,945
Like I said, we were local leaders at the time.

228
00:19:09,765 --> 00:19:11,646
And I think that was just an inspiration for me.

229
00:19:13,726 --> 00:19:20,569
So I know that this is kind of subject to change and the landscape is constantly shifting, but

230
00:19:23,969 --> 00:19:25,692
share whatever you want to share.

231
00:19:26,633 --> 00:19:30,620
What's your current vision for the future of the city of Medford?

232
00:19:33,845 --> 00:19:35,388
One of the things I don't like right now

233
00:19:36,377 --> 00:19:40,518
is we've become a community of old Medford and new Medford.

234
00:19:41,538 --> 00:19:45,039
And we have a divide in the community, and I don't like the divide.

235
00:19:45,119 --> 00:19:47,399
I didn't grow up in a community that was divided.

236
00:19:47,419 --> 00:19:49,039
I grew up in one community.

237
00:19:49,699 --> 00:19:55,640
And that's one of my goals is to bring everybody back to the middle so we're all together as a community.

238
00:19:56,241 --> 00:20:02,702
Even if you just moved here in the last couple of years, people like us who lived here our whole lives, I think we need to be one community.

239
00:20:04,102 --> 00:20:11,206
That's one of my biggest things that I'd like to do if I was elected mayor was get the unity back.

240
00:20:11,447 --> 00:20:14,729
I want the community that we grew up in where everybody was friendly with everybody.

241
00:20:16,570 --> 00:20:18,131
No more us versus them.

242
00:20:21,453 --> 00:20:33,100
So maybe that in some ways at least partially answers the question about how you came to the decision that you wanted to run for mayor.

243
00:20:35,623 --> 00:20:46,389
So it really wasn't in my thoughts up until last year.

244
00:20:47,330 --> 00:20:48,751
And after the last election,

245
00:20:50,764 --> 00:20:53,885
My vote total was quite high, higher than it had ever been.

246
00:20:54,865 --> 00:21:01,967
And some new people came onto the council, and I had to take the back seat.

247
00:21:02,787 --> 00:21:09,168
I'd always been a leader in the council, and now I was on the minority end.

248
00:21:10,729 --> 00:21:12,909
Welcome to my life, okay?

249
00:21:12,989 --> 00:21:14,370
I was on the minority end.

250
00:21:16,650 --> 00:21:18,951
I didn't like sitting there doing nothing every week.

251
00:21:19,691 --> 00:21:28,874
I mean, I voted correctly and everything, but there were some issues that I would have liked to have done, but as they say, if you don't have the votes, you don't have the votes.

252
00:21:29,154 --> 00:21:38,438
So that kind of spurned my decision, and we had a little family meeting at the house, and it didn't go over too well.

253
00:21:39,599 --> 00:21:48,370
with some members of the family, but I moved on and here I am today.

254
00:21:50,553 --> 00:21:51,854
It's been a tough time.

255
00:21:51,874 --> 00:21:54,418
I think my wife will tell you how hard it's been on her.

256
00:21:55,598 --> 00:21:58,819
It's been tough on me, I'm out every day, and it's really been pressing.

257
00:21:59,899 --> 00:22:02,560
It's a lot harder than I ever thought it was gonna be.

258
00:22:02,640 --> 00:22:04,020
Okay, all right, all right.

259
00:22:04,120 --> 00:22:14,823
So you may have, again, you know, because you keep anticipating what I'm gonna ask you, you may already have answered this part of the question, but how does your wife feel about it?

260
00:22:14,863 --> 00:22:16,343
How does Carol feel about it?

261
00:22:20,887 --> 00:22:35,604
I think she's I think she's on board now okay um and I get it it's hard for her mm-hmm I you know I can't keep dragging her everywhere you know she's got her things to do and she's a grandmother you know and yes and it's

