00:22:36,565 --> 00:22:53,787
Taking her away for some things that she likes to do with the kids and I said listen It's only another month away says we can I said you can't I says you gotta stop being a grandma for like the next five weeks Yeah, which is hard for her because you know, she wants to be the grandma absolutely So it's been a little long a little tough.

263
00:22:53,987 --> 00:22:55,229
Okay on all of us.

264
00:22:55,249 --> 00:22:55,269
I

265
00:22:55,609 --> 00:22:58,972
All right, all right.

266
00:22:59,112 --> 00:23:01,654
I've never done this before in an interview.

267
00:23:01,674 --> 00:23:10,560
In a lot of instances, it's because I don't always have the husband and the wife or the partners in a relationship.

268
00:23:11,261 --> 00:23:16,405
So I can't do it, but I can do it tonight because Carol's here too.

269
00:23:18,026 --> 00:23:24,211
So what three words would you use to describe Mrs. Caraviello?

270
00:23:26,543 --> 00:23:27,283
She's my rock.

271
00:23:28,444 --> 00:23:29,404
She's my inspiration.

272
00:23:29,824 --> 00:23:30,164
Okay.

273
00:23:30,524 --> 00:23:33,585
And again, she inspires me to do better.

274
00:23:33,845 --> 00:23:35,326
Okay, okay, all right.

275
00:23:36,186 --> 00:23:38,967
All right, so shout it out, Carol.

276
00:23:39,547 --> 00:23:42,888
What three words would you use to describe Rick?

277
00:23:43,168 --> 00:23:44,288
She can't say that on TV.

278
00:23:44,968 --> 00:23:45,748
Mm-hmm.

279
00:23:59,973 --> 00:24:01,494
I love it.

280
00:24:02,714 --> 00:24:05,536
Okay, all right, there it is, there it is.

281
00:24:07,037 --> 00:24:13,601
So 47 years of marriage is a wonderful thing to make note of.

282
00:24:14,742 --> 00:24:20,145
Okay, what do you know now that you wish you had known day one?

283
00:24:22,867 --> 00:24:23,407
About my wife?

284
00:24:25,248 --> 00:24:26,869
About being with her, you know.

285
00:24:27,129 --> 00:24:27,750
Believe it or not.

286
00:24:29,125 --> 00:24:30,665
I know her better than she knows her.

287
00:24:32,806 --> 00:24:34,366
I know everything about her.

288
00:24:35,286 --> 00:24:39,467
I know, I can tell as soon as I walk in the house with the face on the wall.

289
00:24:39,747 --> 00:24:41,688
I said, you know, I write in, I sense the attitude.

290
00:24:42,568 --> 00:24:47,589
I can read her to a T. Me, I'm a little more complex.

291
00:24:49,189 --> 00:24:55,810
I tell her, I tell her, I says, you know, I says, we've been married 47 years and you still haven't figured me out yet.

292
00:24:56,290 --> 00:24:57,771
I'm a little more complex than she is.

293
00:24:58,931 --> 00:25:04,474
I know I can tell, as soon as I walk in the house, I know if this is a situation, if I've done something wrong.

294
00:25:05,875 --> 00:25:09,737
Yeah, I only have 37 years in, right?

295
00:25:09,797 --> 00:25:11,819
So you got an extra 10 years on me.

296
00:25:12,619 --> 00:25:13,680
I think I know.

297
00:25:14,460 --> 00:25:15,361
But they can fool you.

298
00:25:16,362 --> 00:25:17,143
No, she can't fool me.

299
00:25:19,405 --> 00:25:20,426
I know her to a T. I know.

300
00:25:20,486 --> 00:25:24,250
If I had her sitting in this chair, she'd be saying something different, but that's another story.

301
00:25:24,490 --> 00:25:26,152
That's another story for another time.

302
00:25:26,192 --> 00:25:27,193
That's fantastic.

303
00:25:27,473 --> 00:25:28,314
That's fantastic.

304
00:25:28,654 --> 00:25:34,160
So, you know, you've been at this for a long time and you certainly have got

305
00:25:35,501 --> 00:25:42,645
legacy moments, you've got some wonderful things that you've been able to do or be a part of in city government.

306
00:25:42,705 --> 00:25:45,607
Talk about two or three of the things that you're most proud of.

307
00:25:47,185 --> 00:25:49,947
Probably the most proud of is the Medford Public Library.

308
00:25:50,387 --> 00:25:50,628
Okay.

309
00:25:51,108 --> 00:25:59,293
I worked four years to bring that to Medford, going to the conference every year.

310
00:25:59,313 --> 00:26:02,555
And there'd be a library table there.

311
00:26:02,615 --> 00:26:05,977
It was a convention for municipal governments.

312
00:26:06,157 --> 00:26:06,337
Okay.

313
00:26:08,283 --> 00:26:11,408
I would go there and the library would be open.

314
00:26:11,428 --> 00:26:13,811
I said, you know, that all these communities were getting libraries.

315
00:26:14,592 --> 00:26:16,555
And he says, oh, he says, is Smith on the list?

316
00:26:17,616 --> 00:26:17,777
No.

317
00:26:19,179 --> 00:26:19,499
Oh, jeez.

318
00:26:20,240 --> 00:26:22,824
So after three or four, after the fourth year,

319
00:26:24,566 --> 00:26:25,808
I finally got us on the list.

320
00:26:26,889 --> 00:26:32,615
And the library foundation came to MedFed, and they agreed that we needed a library.

321
00:26:33,476 --> 00:26:41,706
And this is something, so I brought it to Mayor Burke, and Mayor Burke could have told me, Rick, you know, we're not doing it.

322
00:26:43,206 --> 00:26:52,950
But she took it, and between the two of us, we got the $12 million in upfront financing to get the library.

323
00:26:53,970 --> 00:27:01,532
I also sit on the Memphis Public Library Foundation, I'm the co-chair, and we raised another $6 million to help defray the cost.

324
00:27:01,572 --> 00:27:03,273
So in a sense, essentially,

325
00:27:04,053 --> 00:27:11,261
City of Medford has a brand new state-of-the-art library for about 45 cents on the dollar, which in today's thing is a steal.

326
00:27:11,882 --> 00:27:16,908
And that's probably one of the things I'm most proud of, that I could deliver something that to a community.

327
00:27:17,168 --> 00:27:18,770
As a city councilor, not even as a mayor.

328
00:27:19,190 --> 00:27:21,112
And I thank Mayor Burke for her help in doing that too.

329
00:27:22,233 --> 00:27:35,157
I can tell you, with regard to the library, kind of one of the proudest moments that I had as a poet was being asked to write a piece to commemorate the library.

330
00:27:35,197 --> 00:27:41,899
And then when the family came to do the dedication, being asked to read some of it.

331
00:27:45,160 --> 00:27:50,288
I think that that library is like, it's a plum.

332
00:27:50,348 --> 00:27:53,172
Probably getting about 10,000 people a month that go through there.

333
00:27:53,512 --> 00:27:55,595
We have a dedicated children's library now.

334
00:27:56,817 --> 00:27:58,860
You actually have a room where you can have

335
00:28:00,522 --> 00:28:04,746
someone like yourself speak, we bring authors in there.

336
00:28:05,427 --> 00:28:11,513
Be surprised at the amount of people in this community that don't have access to the internet and don't have access to computers.

337
00:28:11,893 --> 00:28:14,015
They go there, they do job interviews there.

338
00:28:15,636 --> 00:28:20,719
You go there between 9 and 11, you can't get in the second floor because it's packed with children.

339
00:28:21,479 --> 00:28:24,840
There's maker space, there's private study rooms.

340
00:28:25,741 --> 00:28:29,483
It's a great building to be in.

341
00:28:30,163 --> 00:28:36,646
That's probably my proudest achievement, that I can bring my own kids back there and say, this is what your father did.

342
00:28:36,826 --> 00:28:37,767
Yeah, yeah.

343
00:28:38,547 --> 00:28:44,172
Well, I've had probably three or four different events in the Bonsignori room.

344
00:28:44,192 --> 00:28:49,916
It's a great, it's one of the great spaces in Medford now for meetings and gatherings.

345
00:28:49,936 --> 00:28:54,400
So if I could give you a little story about the Bonsignori room.

346
00:28:55,440 --> 00:28:56,581
Go for it.

347
00:28:57,642 --> 00:28:58,843
We sold everything in the building.

348
00:28:58,903 --> 00:29:00,865
Chairs, anything, anybody want anything?

349
00:29:01,085 --> 00:29:01,885
We sold everything.

350
00:29:01,905 --> 00:29:02,446
Name it, name it.

351
00:29:02,466 --> 00:29:03,226
We named everything.

352
00:29:04,542 --> 00:29:10,808
I knew Bob Bonsignori a little bit, and he reached out to me and said, geez, Ricky, I'd like to help out in the library, do something.

353
00:29:10,828 --> 00:29:11,729
I said, great.

354
00:29:12,550 --> 00:29:19,156
I says, I'll have the woman, the fundraiser, she'll give you a call, and whatever you want to do, you do.

355
00:29:19,977 --> 00:29:24,581
So I gave him the number, and he calls me back and says, is this guy real?

356
00:29:24,761 --> 00:29:25,682
I says, why?

357
00:29:25,702 --> 00:29:27,183
He says, he's donating $400,000.

358
00:29:29,531 --> 00:29:31,053
for the room, I said, whoa, Jesus.

359
00:29:31,894 --> 00:29:34,096
I was like, taken back.

360
00:29:34,697 --> 00:29:37,600
Because Bob doesn't live, he lives in California now.

361
00:29:38,141 --> 00:29:46,450
But yeah, I was taken back when he came back with, he says, if I give you that much money, will you name it after, and he named it after his mother and father.

362
00:29:46,470 --> 00:29:47,472
And he brought her there,

363
00:29:50,515 --> 00:29:56,638
before the library opened as a surprise to show her that this is what I did for you as a son.

364
00:29:57,738 --> 00:29:59,619
It was a touching moment.

365
00:29:59,999 --> 00:30:06,182
He was one of my guys in high school, Bobby Bonsignore.

366
00:30:06,242 --> 00:30:07,943
I was kind of shocked when he came up with that kind of number.

367
00:30:07,963 --> 00:30:12,925
I thought maybe a couple thousand dollars, but when she said that number, I was like, whoa.

368
00:30:12,945 --> 00:30:15,206
Next time I ask him for some loot, man, I'm going to start it.

369
00:30:16,584 --> 00:30:17,124
He's got plenty.

370
00:30:17,184 --> 00:30:18,504
I'm gonna start at a bigger number.

371
00:30:19,245 --> 00:30:20,505
I'm thinking small here.

372
00:30:22,065 --> 00:30:23,065
Very good, very good.

373
00:30:24,166 --> 00:30:35,208
Okay, so as you think about collaborations and community building in the city of Medford, what gives you the most hope?

374
00:30:38,229 --> 00:30:39,189
I have hope for our city.

375
00:30:39,969 --> 00:30:44,450
And I want to bring it back

376
00:30:46,530 --> 00:30:48,452
to a time when we're all united together.

377
00:30:49,814 --> 00:30:58,845
And again, I think I said this before, I just don't like when I go, even when we have these meetings and people write on social media, you know,

378
00:31:00,100 --> 00:31:03,781
People tell me, one of the knocks on me is, I'm Old Medford.

379
00:31:04,941 --> 00:31:07,082
And I don't understand New Medford.

380
00:31:07,962 --> 00:31:09,983
I am Old Medford, I was born and raised here.

381
00:31:10,323 --> 00:31:12,844
A lot of my friends have since all moved away.

382
00:31:13,164 --> 00:31:13,984
I chose to stay here.

383
00:31:14,304 --> 00:31:17,865
I chose to raise my family here, and send my kids to school here.

384
00:31:18,405 --> 00:31:19,626
I'm really proud of that fact.

385
00:31:21,166 --> 00:31:24,647
And when people tell me that I'm Old Medford and I don't get it, they're wrong, I do get it.

386
00:31:25,267 --> 00:31:26,228
I do get it, and I want,

387
00:31:27,668 --> 00:31:30,289
The new people in Memphis that moved here, I want them to get it too.

388
00:31:30,629 --> 00:31:34,770
I want them to know the community that I grew up in and that you grew up in.

389
00:31:34,790 --> 00:31:36,030
Many of these people in this room grew up in.

390
00:31:36,590 --> 00:31:38,050
I want that community back again.

391
00:31:38,431 --> 00:31:39,251
I want the closeness.

392
00:31:39,311 --> 00:31:41,711
I want people to walk around the streets and be friendly.

393
00:31:41,791 --> 00:31:45,812
I don't like when people walk by my house and neighbors and they don't even say hello anymore.

394
00:31:46,212 --> 00:31:47,373
You don't know your neighbor anymore.

395
00:31:48,033 --> 00:31:48,473
That's not...

396
00:31:49,413 --> 00:31:51,195
That's not what I like.

397
00:31:51,716 --> 00:31:53,117
You know me, I'm a friendly guy.

398
00:31:53,397 --> 00:31:56,441
But I want that unity back in our community.

399
00:31:56,541 --> 00:31:58,022
I want the community that I grew up in.

400
00:31:58,583 --> 00:31:59,904
And I want everybody to be together.

401
00:32:00,585 --> 00:32:01,226
Okay, all right.

402
00:32:01,246 --> 00:32:04,269
So that's the hope that you have.

403
00:32:05,310 --> 00:32:08,333
Again, it may answer some of the next question.

404
00:32:09,114 --> 00:32:10,255
What gives you Ajita?

405
00:32:13,670 --> 00:32:17,333
Um, I don't know.

406
00:32:17,393 --> 00:32:20,855
On a personal basis, or on a government basis?

407
00:32:20,875 --> 00:32:25,718
Well, let's try to avoid the politics, because you end up calling somebody a name, and we don't want that.

408
00:32:27,239 --> 00:32:32,522
Yeah, kind of on a personal, but kind of an expansive personal basis.

409
00:32:33,303 --> 00:32:34,804
What keeps you up late at night?

410
00:32:35,524 --> 00:32:37,786
What makes you take that second antacid?

411
00:32:41,007 --> 00:32:45,349
I'm kind of a sensitive person, and I don't like when people talk bad about our community.

412
00:32:46,469 --> 00:32:48,370
That doesn't sit well with me.

413
00:32:48,710 --> 00:32:52,892
Like I said, I take pride in my community.

414
00:32:54,092 --> 00:32:59,234
I love and I care, and I have concern for our community.

415
00:32:59,875 --> 00:33:01,455
That's really what keeps me up at night.

416
00:33:02,856 --> 00:33:06,437
And again, people know when you call, I want to be there.

417
00:33:08,098 --> 00:33:08,778
I want to help people.

418
00:33:10,078 --> 00:33:16,100
I've made my last probably 35 years of my life helping people.

419
00:33:17,080 --> 00:33:18,240
And I want to continue doing that.

420
00:33:18,840 --> 00:33:19,281
Very good.

421
00:33:19,561 --> 00:33:20,001
Very good.

422
00:33:21,981 --> 00:33:30,383
How do you think what you've learned during your tenure as a city councilor will inform how you move forward as a potential mayor of Medford?

423
00:33:31,260 --> 00:33:33,403
I've learned a lot, like I said, over the years.

424
00:33:34,043 --> 00:33:36,606
I'm certainly not the same person I was 12 years ago.

425
00:33:37,047 --> 00:33:38,368
I've grown on the job, I've learned.

426
00:33:39,550 --> 00:33:42,213
I understand more now how government runs.

427
00:33:44,175 --> 00:33:47,319
When you're the new guy, my first year, you had all these ideas.

428
00:33:48,362 --> 00:33:49,302
I was going to change the world.

429
00:33:50,163 --> 00:33:53,544
And you learn quickly, it's not happening.

430
00:33:53,804 --> 00:33:54,445
It's not happening.

431
00:33:55,345 --> 00:34:01,428
The ideas that you have don't come to fruition because I didn't understand how government worked.

432
00:34:02,308 --> 00:34:07,791
And people try to equate the private world and the government world.

433
00:34:07,851 --> 00:34:10,172
And I come from private business.

434
00:34:11,192 --> 00:34:11,773
It doesn't work.

435
00:34:11,833 --> 00:34:14,094
It's not the same mentality.

436
00:34:14,935 --> 00:34:18,678
As a business owner, you make a decision today and it happens tomorrow.

437
00:34:19,458 --> 00:34:24,922
You make a decision in government, well, we have to form a committee and do a study or bring in a consultant.

438
00:34:25,343 --> 00:34:29,225
